Dialogue: 0,0:00:08.63,0:00:10.63,Default,,0,0,0,,District Court of Potsdam
Dialogue: 0,0:00:11.00,0:00:14.95,Default,,0,0,0,,10 December 1955
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.95,0:00:19.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Verdict in trial for quadruple murder
Dialogue: 0,0:00:19.00,0:00:22.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Defendant: Wilhelm Antonius Wehren,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.55,0:00:27.37,Default,,0,0,0,,born on 30 May 1918 in Essen.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.37,0:00:31.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Place of crime: \NHerzsprung, near Wittstock (on the Dosse).
Dialogue: 0,0:00:31.63,0:00:36.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Date of crime: 30 April 1945.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:36.72,0:00:43.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Victims: Prisoners of Polish nationality, \Nidentity unknown.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.17,0:00:46.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Willi Wehren is 21 when the war begins.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.50,0:00:51.48,Default,,0,0,0,,In the summer of 1939, \Nhe is drafted into the Wehrmacht.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:51.48,0:00:55.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Wehren soon attracts negative attention:
Dialogue: 0,0:00:55.10,0:01:00.25,Default,,0,0,0,,accused of slander and the receipt of stolen goods, \Nhe is tried by a military tribunal.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.25,0:01:05.00,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1943, \Nhe is ultimately accused of undermining military morale.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.65,0:01:08.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Wehren is sent to Sachsenhausen Concentration Camp.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.97,0:01:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It seems his fate is sealed.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.00,0:01:15.95,Default,,0,0,0,,But in April 1945, his fortunes turn.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:16.00,0:01:18.12,Default,,0,0,0,,The war’s end is looming.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.12,0:01:21.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The concentration camp is to be evacuated.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:21.00,0:01:25.12,Default,,0,0,0,,To do so, the SS also enlists inmates as guards.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:27.12,0:01:31.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Willi Wehren is recruited as well,\Nand is put in uniform again.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.50,0:01:38.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Issued with a rifle and ammunition, \Nhe’s assigned to a column of five hundred women.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:38.40,0:01:43.03,Default,,0,0,0,,On 22 April, \Nthey set off on the long journey to the north.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.03,0:01:47.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Theirs is the last group to march from Sachsenhausen.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.25,0:01:55.24,Default,,0,0,0,,They wear little more than \Ntheir threadbare prisoners’ uniforms.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.44,0:01:56.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Not all of them have shoes.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.10,0:02:02.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Many walk in wooden clogs \Nor improvise with rags wrapped around their feet.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.60,0:02:04.58,Default,,0,0,0,,They walk day after day.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.58,0:02:07.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Sometimes it’s 40 km, sometimes 20 km.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.40,0:02:10.40,Default,,0,0,0,,The thermometer barely gets gets above 0°C.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:10.90,0:02:14.11,Default,,0,0,0,,They sometimes find a barn for the night.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.11,0:02:19.45,Default,,0,0,0,,But more often,\Nthey sleep out in the open.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.00,0:02:22.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Meanwhile, Wehren continues his rise.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.75,0:02:25.07,Default,,0,0,0,,He receives a motorcycle.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.07,0:02:28.87,Default,,0,0,0,,As a despatch rider, \Nhe maintains contact between marching groups.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:29.17,0:02:32.10,Default,,0,0,0,,He also has to look after the provisioning \Nof his assigned group.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.08,0:02:35.58,Default,,0,0,0,,The march is torturous.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:35.58,0:02:38.58,Default,,0,0,0,,The prisoners are weakened by their long internment.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.58,0:02:41.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Many are sick and starved.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.40,0:02:46.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Those who can’t keep up are shot by the SS \Nand kicked into the ditch.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.80,0:02:56.61,Default,,0,0,0,,More than a thousand dead are left on the roads and fields.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.71,0:03:00.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Whoever can, keeps going.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.48,0:03:04.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Endless processions of misery traverse the roads and villages.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:05.38,0:03:07.70,Default,,0,0,0,,There’s well over thirty thousand people.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:07.70,0:03:09.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Everyone can see them.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.45,0:03:13.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Hardly anyone feels sympathy for the prisoners,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.60,0:03:17.89,Default,,0,0,0,,and very few have the courage to help them.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:18.29,0:03:22.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Most react with mistrust, fear, or indifference.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.22,0:03:27.33,Default,,0,0,0,,So too in the little village of Herzsprung.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:35.13,0:03:38.89,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s here in this village that Willi Wehren has abandoned his unit.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.00,0:03:42.00,Default,,0,0,0,,He meets a man named Berger.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.30,0:03:46.70,Default,,0,0,0,,This is another ex-prisoner who was hastily put in uniform
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.70,0:03:48.73,Default,,0,0,0,,when the death march began.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:48.89,0:03:52.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Wehren has taken up residence at the local inn.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.80,0:03:55.00,Default,,0,0,0,,He knows the innkeeper from before:
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.14,0:03:58.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Wilhelm Leppin is an important man in Herzsprung.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:58.22,0:04:02.31,Default,,0,0,0,,He owns the inn and is also the local Nazi Party chief.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:02.51,0:04:11.22,Default,,0,0,0,,In this village, he’s in charge\N ... and the locals follow him willingly.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.22,0:04:13.13,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s Monday, the 30th of April.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:13.53,0:04:17.98,Default,,0,0,0,,In the morning, \Na 10-year-old boy comes running up to Leppin:
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.08,0:04:22.85,Default,,0,0,0,,his mother has found four runaway prisoners in the barn!
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.95,0:04:27.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Leppin, Wehren, and Berger\Nimmediately rush to the woman’s farm
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.90,0:04:34.32,Default,,0,0,0,,and find four frightened Polish prisoners\Nwho had managed to escape the death march.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.60,0:04:36.02,Default,,0,0,0,,They force them out of hiding.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.02,0:04:38.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Wehren starts beating them.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.20,0:04:40.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Leppin finds a cudgel.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.02,0:04:43.02,Default,,0,0,0,,He likewise beats them and yells:
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.20,0:04:45.13,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}‘Come out here, you swine!’{\i0}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.30,0:04:49.60,Default,,0,0,0,,The three men talk it over.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.90,0:04:51.90,Default,,0,0,0,,They don’t want any hassle.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.04,0:04:54.82,Default,,0,0,0,,To them, the Poles are a burden.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.00,0:04:59.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Leppin decides it’d be best to get rid of them.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.92,0:05:09.76,Default,,0,0,0,,A family in Herzsprung is getting ready to flee \Nfrom the approaching Red Army.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.79,0:05:13.81,Default,,0,0,0,,They suddenly hear a clamour outside their window.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.00,0:05:17.36,Default,,0,0,0,,The Polish prisoners are being herded through Herzsprung,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.46,0:05:22.10,Default,,0,0,0,,across the village road \Nand past the local homes to the village outskirts.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.70,0:05:29.22,Default,,0,0,0,,The family watches the entourage with its trail of curious onlookers,\N including several children.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.32,0:05:41.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Just before the gravel pit, on a small tree-covered slope,\Nthe procession comes to a halt.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.47,0:05:44.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Among them is the local Nazi official Leppin.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.90,0:05:50.28,Default,,0,0,0,,He stays somewhat apart, smoking a cigar,\Nbut follows the proceedings closely.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.90,0:05:52.90,Default,,0,0,0,,A scuffle begins.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:52.90,0:05:55.22,Default,,0,0,0,,One of the prisoners tries to escape.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:55.22,0:05:57.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Willi Wehren chases him and shoots.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:58.32,0:06:01.26,Default,,0,0,0,,The victim goes down, but is still alive.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.56,0:06:08.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Wehren flips him over with his foot and kills him\N with a shot to the back of the neck.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.31,0:06:22.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Berger and Wehren now force the remaining prisoners\Naround the slope to Herzsprung’s gravel pit.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.04,0:06:26.39,Default,,0,0,0,,What happens next is not visible to the onlookers.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.32,0:06:31.13,Default,,0,0,0,,But the tommy gun’s shots still echo through the whole village.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.00,0:06:33.13,Default,,0,0,0,,[shoots firing]
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.13,0:06:35.26,Default,,0,0,0,,[shoots firing]
Dialogue: 0,0:06:37.14,0:06:38.27,Default,,0,0,0,,[shoots firing]
Dialogue: 0,0:06:43.23,0:06:46.70,Default,,0,0,0,,The villagers watch transfixed.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:46.70,0:06:54.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Seven witnesses claim they saw or heard\N the execution of the camp prisoners.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.67,0:07:01.39,Default,,0,0,0,,They testify that other villagers\N also followed the events from close up.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.70,0:07:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,On 10 December 1955,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:08.00,0:07:13.97,Default,,0,0,0,,the Potsdam District Court sentences \NWilhelm Wehren to death for quadruple murder.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.10,0:07:19.54,Default,,0,0,0,,A year later,\N his sentence is commuted to life imprisonment.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:20.12,0:07:25.76,Default,,0,0,0,,In August 1975,\NWehren is pardoned and released from prison.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.16,0:07:28.76,Default,,0,0,0,,He moves to West Germany.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:30.39,0:07:35.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Leppin is arrested by the Soviet military authorities in May 1945.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.33,0:07:40.10,Default,,0,0,0,,As a Nazi Party official, \Nhe is sent to an internment camp.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.71,0:07:43.67,Default,,0,0,0,,He is released in August 1948.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.47,0:07:47.97,Default,,0,0,0,,He is never charged for the murders in Herzsprung.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:48.67,0:07:52.13,Default,,0,0,0,,The case against Leppin is dismissed \Ndue to his {\i1}‘minor responsibility’{\i0}.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.43,0:07:55.73,Default,,0,0,0,,He remains unpunished.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.13,0:08:02.94,Default,,0,0,0,,A denunciation, a capture, a public execution.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.54,0:08:09.35,Default,,0,0,0,,In broad daylight, in the middle of the village, in view of the people.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.75,0:08:13.90,Default,,0,0,0,,They stick together, \Nand beyond the mass murder too:
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.32,0:08:21.25,Default,,0,0,0,,the bodies are quickly buried, and with them, \Nthe knowledge of that heinous event.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.75,0:08:24.35,Default,,0,0,0,,In Herzsprung, a silence gradually settles.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.65,0:08:28.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Soon, there is no one here \Nwho still remembers the Polish prisoners
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.45,0:08:31.21,Default,,0,0,0,,that were executed in the village.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.31,0:08:35.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Their names remain unknown.
